.TH "sti_hqvdp_check_hw_scaling" 9 "sti_hqvdp_check_hw_scaling" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
sti_hqvdp_check_hw_scaling \- 
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "bool" sti_hqvdp_check_hw_scaling
.BI "(struct sti_hqvdp *hqvdp "  ","
.BI "struct drm_display_mode *mode "  ","
.BI "int src_w "  ","
.BI "int src_h "  ","
.BI "int dst_w "  ","
.BI "int dst_h "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "hqvdp" 12
hqvdp pointer
.IP "mode" 12
display mode with timing constraints
.IP "src_w" 12
source width
.IP "src_h" 12
source height
.IP "dst_w" 12
destination width
.IP "dst_h" 12
destination height
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Check if the HW is able to perform the scaling request
The firmware scaling limitation is "CEIL(1/Zy) <= FLOOR(LFW)" where:
Zy = OutputHeight / InputHeight
LFW = (Tx * IPClock) / (MaxNbCycles * Cp)
Tx : Total video mode horizontal resolution
IPClock : HQVDP IP clock (Mhz)
MaxNbCycles: max(InputWidth, OutputWidth)
Cp: Video mode pixel clock (Mhz)
.SH "RETURN"
True if the HW can scale.
